title: For Sale/Trade:  80% LOWER RECEIVER FOR AR-15 ONLY
postcontent:
An 80% lower receiver is a partially completed piece of metal that requires special tooling and skills to be completed, a trigger assembly, and a complete upper to be considered a firearm. Unlike a stripped receiver it is not required to be transferred through a Federal Firearms Licensed holder (FFL).
These are high quality 80% lowers made from 7075 t6 aircraft grade aluminium with fully broached magazine wells for perfect dropping al ALL magazines. They are made to 100% military specifications and will work with any Mil Spec Jig although I recommend the ones made for these lowers cause they work very well and come with all of the drill bits need to complete the job as well as detailed instructions. They come with a bead-blasted raw aluminium finish that looks very good as-is or is ready for paint. These are the ONLY 80% receivers on the market that have been given permission by the ATF to have the rear pocket area that the rear take-down inserts into already milled out for you. One of the most troublesome areas to drill out and its already done for you. Now you don't have to worry about the rear take-down pin detent bore being ruined as it is all perfectly milled to spec.

Unlike a stripped receiver it is not required to be transferred through a Federal Firearms Licensed holder (FFL).
These are high quality 80% lowers made from 7075 t6 aircraft grade aluminium with fully broached magazine wells for perfect dropping al ALL magazines. They are made to 100% military specifications and will work with any Mil Spec Jig although I recommend the ones made for these lowers cause they work very well and come with all of the drill bits need to complete the job as well as detailed instructions. They come with a bead-blasted raw aluminium finish that looks very good as-is or is ready for paint. These are the ONLY 80% receivers on the market that have been given permission by the ATF to have the rear pocket area that the rear take-down inserts into already milled out for you. One of the most troublesome areas to drill out and its already done for you. Now you don't have to worry about the rear take-down pin detent bore being ruined as it is all perfectly milled to spec.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Federal Auto Match 22LR Trade for Federal Champion 22LR or Comparable
location: Beloit Township, south of, Janesville, Wisconsin
postcontent:
I have been acquiring Federal Auto Match 22 LR in anticipation of buying another .22 Semi-auto rifle. I finally bought that rifle last week and subsequently took it to the range 3 times, using different ammo each time. 
As clean as the Auto Match is, this rifle does not like the nose of the cartridge and sometimes hangs up on the feed ramp.
It cycles the cheaper and dirtier Federal Champion 22LR better. It even eats the dirty Remington Golden bullets without much of a problem.
Every semi-auto I fired Auto Match in previously cycled  flawlessly. This ammo is made for semi-autos and has a pretty clean burning powder. It cycles great in my 22 pistol and my marlin 60, but this new one cycles better with the cheaper ammo.
I have a full case of the Auto match, and would like to trade some or all of it for Federal Champion 36 grain copper plated 22LR or Winchester M-22.I'd trade round for round of these. I'd even consider trading some of it for Remington Golden bullets if they were the ones that say NEW AND IMPROVED on the box, but it would have to be one box of auto match for two 225 round boxes of the Remington, because I'll have to spend  more money in cleaning supplies if I shoot that and extra time cleaning.
I am open to reasonable offers as long as it's not "aguila" or anything like that. If you need or want some Auto Match 22LR and have some of the cheaper Federal Champion 22LR or something similar to trade, let me know. I am open to reasonable trades. The key word is REASONABLE.
I would consider selling the Federal Auto Match outright too, but it would have to be $35.00 a box simply because it would cost that or more to replace it, plus I'll have to spend the next 6 months trying to find the other ammo that cycles in this rifle.
